title: M1 Garand, 6-digit Serial Number, 1942
postcontent:
M1 Garand - "the greatest battle implement ever devised".

This one has a brand new, never-been-fired Criterion barrel and a new walnut stock.  The overall finish is a combination of original and new finish, which is done to balance out the overall appearance of the rifle.  This is not a collector piece (other then the cool S/N and manufacture date), it is meant to be a shooter.  I shoot in matches, and this was intended to be my next match rifle.

Price.  A plain-jane Garand will set you back about $700-1000, depending on a lot of things.  One thing this rifle has going for it is the fact that it's built on a WWII receiver, from 1942.  The reason it is not being sold as a collector is because the rest of the parts are not original to the rifle, and have been selected for fit since its' purpose was to be a match rifle.

I am in a position where I am primarily interested in silver or gold, and potential trades.  Trades could include, but are not limited to:  Ammo, rifles, rifle parts, reloading tools and (sealed) components, and metalworking equipment.  I shoot in a .22 pistol league, and could see me trading straight-up for the right high-end target pistol.  The price in silver is 42 ounces, payable in American Eagles.

title: Winchester Model 98 Ranger in 30-30
postcontent:
The classic lever gun.  This is a Winchester 98 Angle Eject, sold as the "Ranger" model.  It is a later production rifle that has seen fairly light use, but is not really a collector.  A good hunting rifle that's light, in a caliber that takes deer easily.  I have a hand reloading kit for this one, good for throwing in a pack and being self-sufficient for a while, as well as quite a bit of brass and some factory ammo.  Since the receiver was tapped for scope mounts, it also has a Leupold one-piece scope mount and a Bushnell scope on it that fits the rifle very well.

The bummer - the guy I bought it from tried to mount a peep sight on the left hand side of the receiver.  There is a hole there, but it does not in any way affect action or safety.  As a result, the price for this one is quite attractive.  Trades are always entertained.  The price in silver is 12 ounces, payable in American Eagles.  If you were to buy silver today, that would be $240.  Federal reserve notes pay 10% higher.

title: KIMBER PRO ECLIPSE II (customized)
postcontent:
KIMBER PRO ECLIPSE II (From The Custom Shop), 45ACP; Has a 4 lb. custom trigger, 4" Match Grade Bushingless Bull Barrel; Kimber Fixed 3 Dot Tritium Night Sights; Stainless Steel Slide & Frame; Front strap Checkering (30LPI); 1-8RD Magazine; Diamond Checkered Laminated Wood Grips; Ambidextrous Safety; Adjustable Trigger. This pistol has the internal extractor and Kimber Series II safety. The pistol comes with original box, paperwork, and one 8 round Kimber magazine. 

The pistol was sent to Ron Mahovsky and the Metalife hard chrome finish was applied over the blackened stainless steel. The Metalife finish, otherwise known as SS Chromium M. Metalife looks like stainless steel, but has a hardness of about 71 on the Rockwell Scale, which is even harder than stainless steel. It is guaranteed not to chip, crack or peel when applied to metal in good condition, and it is highly rust resistant and holster-wear resistant. The Metalife process cost over $155.00 not including shipping. If you scratch this pistol, you can use a little water on a rag and MAKE THE SCRATCH GO AWAY. It's AWESOME!

Not looking for any trades at this time EXCEPT a nice SVT40, you must pass a NICS check to purchase this pistol.

title: Matched pair of genuine 1860 model Colt Calvary Commemorative black powder Cap & Ball Revolvers-Unfired!
postcontent:
Taking Bids and offers
This U.S. Cavalry Colt Commemorative Matched Set is comprised of Two 1860 Army revolvers chambered for .44 percussion calibers. The barrels are 8 inches long and the cylinders are non-fluted with roll engraved naval scenes. The grips are one piece walnut. The barrels, cylinders, back straps and triggers are blued and the loading levers, frames and hammers are color case hardened. The trigger guards are brass and all remaining parts and screws are a combination of blue and color case hardened finishes. The barrel markings on the left side of each revolver are "United States Cavalry Commemorative". Markings across the top of the barrel are "ADDRESS SAML COLT HARTFORD CT" The total production of this model is 2974 in 1978. The serial numbers of this set are US439 and 439US. The case is oiled American walnut with blue velvet in the bottom and the lid. The outside of the lid has a brass plaque with a cavalryman and the inscription "United States Cavalry Commemorative 1777-1977". This set also comes with some special features including a brass and walnut shoulder stock, which is serialized to match the set with the "US" prefix. Powder flask, a bullet mold and a cap can accompany this issue. The initials on the grips of these guns are "MSK", which are the inspector's initials. The guns in this set are in excellent condition and unfired. The shoulder stock is also mint. . The case is in excellent shape, as well.
